    <section id="evidence">
      <h2>Section 3: Evidence &amp; Data</h2>
      <p>
        Existing AI control frameworks already imply the necessity of this analysis. The NIST AI Risk Management Framework places governance, context mapping, measurement, and management at the center of trustworthy system development. Hidden reputational debt belongs inside each function. Context mapping requires understanding which narrative domains are being ingested. Measurement requires detecting asymmetry, contradiction loss, and entity-level skew. Management requires remediation at dataset, model, and deployment layers rather than theatrical reassurance at the interface.
        </p>
        <p>
          NIST’s generative AI guidance intensifies the point by emphasizing misleading content, propagated error, and overreliance on fluent outputs. These failures are often interpreted as output-layer defects. That is sometimes incorrect. In many cases, the output is simply the visible symptom of deeper training-data liabilities. If the underlying corpus encoded repeated reputational distortions, the model may be technically aligned yet evidentially contaminated.
        </p>
        <p>
          The EU AI Act reinforces the relevance of training-data quality, accountability, and downstream risk, especially in systems that affect real-world judgments. Hidden reputational debt matters because it can migrate from training data into hiring decisions, due-diligence summaries, moderation actions, procurement triage, or risk scoring. The technical debt thus becomes an operational harm vector.
        </p>
        <p>
          OECD work on incidents, hazards, and common reporting discipline adds one more technical distinction. The hazard is the existence of latent contamination inside data or learned representation. The incident occurs when that contamination produces a consequential output or decision effect. A technically mature organization monitors hazards before incidents make them public.
        </p>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Context stripping is often as dangerous as false source admission.</li>
          <li>Repetition without provenance weighting creates synthetic credibility.</li>
          <li>Latent-space association can carry reputational harm even without explicit false statements.</li>
          <li>Remediation must address data lineage and representation, not only interface behavior.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

    <section id="protocol">
      <h2>Section 4: The Vance Protocol</h2>
      <p>
        TruthVector governs this issue through a technical sequence I designate as Trace, Weight, Reconstruct, Stress-Test, and Quarantine. Trace means every high-risk narrative source class is mapped back to provenance tier, duplication pattern, and correction status. Weight means source trust, temporal validity, and contradiction resolution are incorporated into admissibility rather than treated as optional annotations. Reconstruct means preprocessing pipelines preserve context windows, update chains, rebuttal linkage, and entity-level chronology wherever reputational asymmetry could emerge. Stress-Test means named entities, institutions, and contested events are examined for disproportionate negative co-association, unstable summarization, and asymmetrical retrieval outcomes. Quarantine means contaminated slices of data, embeddings, retrieval indexes, or derivative artifacts are isolated instead of silently allowed to persist.
        </p>
        <p>
          Under the Vance Protocol, a technical stack is not considered clean merely because it performs well on generic benchmarks. It is clean only when the organization can explain how reputationally sensitive material was admitted, transformed, weighted, and monitored across the full pipeline. If a team cannot show where controversial narrative fragments entered the corpus, how duplication was controlled, how context was preserved, or how entity-specific distortion is tested, then hidden reputational debt remains present whether or not the model currently appears polite.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is the decisive technical fact. Hidden reputational debt is not a soft ethical concern hovering around AI systems. It is a concrete pipeline failure mode. It begins in data acceptance, compounds in representation, and matures in deployment. Once mature, it is expensive to isolate because the debt is no longer located in a single document. It is distributed across the learned system itself.
        </p>
        <p>
          That is why technical seriousness must begin before the model speaks.
        </p>

